1:44:54 As of Webpack 5.x, you can actually use a spread operator (sort of?) to extend the existing minimizers rather than having to know what's missing and add them.
For example: 

optimization: {
        minimize: true,
        minimizer: [
            // For webpack@5 you can use the `...` syntax to extend existing minimizers (i.e. `terser-webpack-plugin`), uncomment the next line
            `...`,
            new CssMinimizerPlugin()
        ]
    }

If anyone is receiving the error  Error: Automatic publicPath is not supported in this browser when building in the the Html-loader, File-loader, & Clean-webpack chapter, you need to add modify the output property of the webpack.prod.js to include a public path of './'. The public path needs to specified or it won't build it.

webpack.dev.js should look like this:

module.exports = merge(common, {
    mode: "production",
    output: {
        filename: "main.[contenthash].js",
        path: path.resolve(__dirname, "dist"),
        publicPath: "/"
    }
});


webpack.prod.js should look like this: 

module.exports = merge(common, {
    mode: "production",
    output: {
        filename: "main.[contenthash].js",
        path: path.resolve(__dirname, "dist"),
        publicPath: "./"
    }
});

Here's the stackoverflow post I found: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28846814/what-does-publicpath-in-webpack-do

If someone get an error like this: "if (!scriptUrl) throw new Error("Automatic pub  licPath is not supported in this browser");", you need to add publicPath to your options for file-loader in webpack.common.js : use: {
              loader: "file-loader",
              options: {
                name:"[name].[hash].[ext]",
                outputPath:"imgs",
                publicPath:'./imgs',
              }

then it is working :)

